Harry Potter's Literary Magic
Princeton — — This summer, readers around the world celebrated the 20th anniversary of the first book in J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series — — Harry Potter and the Sorcerer’s Stone (which was renamed in the United States as Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone in some editions, but more commonly as Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone). They had good reason to celebrate.
Since this young wizard first appeared on June 26, 1997, "the boy who lived" has become a "symbol of resilience and perseverance".
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, been translated into over 70 languages, and sold a total of 450 million copies.
The eight movies based on this book have grossed a total of $7 billion, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have earned an additional $7 billion in revenue.
For people of a certain age and with a literary mind, it's hard to imagine a day when global audiences weren't captivated by Rowling's work.
So, every time I think back on my students' poor reaction to "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" in the fall of 1999, I'm still surprised, as I had included that book in the syllabus for my popular literature course at Princeton University. I've been teaching the "American Bestsellers" series since 1993.
The course explores popular works from the 17th century to the present, inviting students to think about why and how these bestsellers appeal to their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I ask students to choose a final book that represents the popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
That year, Potter attacked the American coast fiercely.
In June, the American publisher of this series of works urgently pushed the hardcover edition of "Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets," the second book in the series, into bookstores.
The institution also published the third book in the series, "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban," on September 8, as well as the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone."
By the end of the month, Rowling's novel had taken the top three spots on The New York Times bestseller list, and the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" had crowned the top spot on the paperback book sales list.
Even Time magazine put the bespectacled wizard on its cover.
Harry Potter's image is ubiquitous wherever one looks.
My students were eager to know why such a frenzy existed.
Good heavens, they were disappointed.
In their opinion, the Harry Potter series was nothing more than second-rate nonsense, and in comparison to the beloved series from their childhood, such as The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings, it was utterly inferior.
Although their childhood had just passed a few years ago, they criticized Harry Potter just like many notorious adult critics: "it's fabricated," "the writing is bad," "it's clichéd," "it's annoying."

In their view, Harry lacked both miracles and wisdom and warmth.
The students' disgust surprised me at the time, but in retrospect, it was not so astonishing.
Although adults made up a large part of the audience for Harry Potter from the start, these students were precisely in the wrong age range to objectively understand the Harry Potter phenomenon.
They had passed the age of accepting new children's literature, but were still too young and had not yet had their own children (I had just had a child at the time), and they were eager to insist that although the Harry series was currently very popular, it would soon be forgotten.
In the second autumn of 2000, the next batch of students also chose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" as their final analysis text, just like their peers before them, they confidently rejected this work.
Let's fast forward to the spring of 2007.
After putting the course on hold for a few years, I taught "American Bestsellers" again.
When students chose their final analysis text, they chose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone".
And I was prepared to meet their criticisms.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
This is a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who first read Rowling's works not as university students, but as teenagers, just entering the adolescent stage. This means they grew up together with Harry, Ron, and Hermione.
The same thing happened in the autumn of 2010.
For these students, "we grew up with Harry Potter" had become a motto, rather than a label.
Will Harry fade from memory?
As long as we are still alive, that's impossible.
I have taught the bestseller course twice since 2010, and both times, the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final comments.
Are they tired of Harry?
This seems unlikely based on the comments the Harry series received in my other course, "Children's Literature," where I taught Rowling's works.
Now, I choose to include a Harry Potter novel in the curriculum, but I didn't choose "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone," instead, I chose "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban" – it's my favorite in the seven-book series, marking the transition from children's literature to young adult fiction, with complex descriptions of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and sorrow.
My many students also liked this book the most.
But how long can the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Every time I teach children's literature, I first conduct a poll: "Which books from the list did you read during your childhood?"
In 2010, 86% of people had read "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban".
In 2012, this number rose to 94%.
But in the years that followed, the percentage continued to decline — 87% in 2014, and down to 81% in 2016.
These are not scientific, I know.
But I'm curious: when I teach "Children's Literature" again in the spring, will the percentage of students who have read Harry Potter be below 80%?
Will the fact prove that the students from 1999 to 2000 were right, that Harry Potter's status is constantly declining and will never become an eternal classic?
Or is there a turning point ahead, where the percentage will stabilize and no longer decline?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I'm happy to have invited him into my classroom.
